,"1185":"1185","1140":"1140","about 1185":"about 1185","Aberdeen, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bruin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a personal name based on Middle Dutch <i>bruun</i> ‘brown’, or a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion. Compare   De Bruin   and   Bruyn  .","English: of uncertain origin. It may, as Reaney suggested, reflect a pronunciation of French   Brun   ‘brown’.","Altered form of Swiss <b>Bruhin</b>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewin","meanings":["English (mainly Leicestershire): variant of   Bruin  .","Irish (Sligo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Braoin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Braon</i>’, a byname meaning ‘moisture, drop’."]},{"name":"De Bruin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Maarten, Gerrit, Hendrik, Annick, Cornelis, Marinus.","Dutch: variant, with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, of   Bruin   ‘brown’, a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion."]},{"name":"Bruins","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Albertus, Berend, Dirk, Gerrit.","Dutch: patronymic from   Bruin  ."]},{"name":"Bruinsma","meanings":["West Frisian: patronymic, formed with the suffix <i>-ma</i> ‘(one of the) men of’, from a genitivized form of the personal name   Bruin  ."]},{"name":"Bruyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Dirk.","Dutch: variant of   Bruin  ."]}]},{"name":"Walterus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walter","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Walterus de Bruin de  Lusignan was born in 1105, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Agnes Brun in 1125, in Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1199, in Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1105–1199":"1105–1199","1112–1185":"1112–1185","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1140–1199":"1140–1199","1144–1199":"1144–1199","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","1145":"1145","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","1199":"1199","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Aberdeen, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Abe